{
  "doc_id": "17949",
  "text": "During zebrafish gastrulation, progenitor cells become motile and undergo extensive migration to form the ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm germ layers. While ectodermal progenitors assemble in a pseudo-epithelial cell layer, mesodermal and endodermal (mesendodermal) progenitor cells display a highly motile mesenchymal phenotype with a mixture of lamellipodia and bleb-like protrusions [CITATION_1] . Interfering with the ratio of those protrusion types has been shown to lower the directionality but not the speed of their migration [CITATION_2] . Besides mesendodermal progenitors, primordial germ cells (PGCs) also undergo extensive migration during gastrulation but nearly exclusively use bleb-like protrusions for their migration [CITATION_3] . Although using different protrusion types, migration speed and directionality of PGCs and mesendodermal progenitors appear surprisingly similar [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , raising questions as to the choice and benefit of certain protrusion types over others for the migration of the different progenitor cell types during gastrulation.",
